# Target-View Temporal VGGT Architecture

## 1. Goal

Implement a new temporal VGGT model that predicts the VGGT cached features for an intermediate target date `t2` using cached VGGT features from endpoint dates `t1` and `t3`.

The model does not assume that `t1` and `t2` views are aligned. Instead, it explicitly uses the `t2` camera views as the target output canvas.

The model predicts the four VGGT cached layers that are normally passed into the VGGT DPT point-map head:

```text
[4, 11, 17, 23]
```

The VGGT point-map head remains frozen. The model is trained only through cached-feature supervision.

At inference time, the model uses:

```text
t1 cached features
t3 cached features
t1 camera views
t3 camera views
t2 camera views
time/date features
```

It does not use `t2` RGB images at inference.

---

## 2. High-Level Architecture

The model is a target-view temporal decoder.

The main idea is:

```text
t1 cached features + t1 rays
t3 cached features + t3 rays
        ↓
source memory tokens

learned t2 query tokens + t2 rays
        ↓
target-view query tokens

target-view query tokens cross-attend to source memory
        ↓
predicted t2 cached layers
        ↓
frozen VGGT point head
        ↓
predicted t2 point map
```

Unlike the residual endpoint model, this architecture does not use:

```text
pred_t2_cache = f1_cache + update
```

because `t1` and `t2` are not assumed to be view-consistent.

Instead, the model generates the `t2` cached feature grid from target-view query tokens.

---

## 3. Inputs

For each training sample, the model receives:

```text
cached_t1_layers
cached_t3_layers
camera_t1
camera_t3
camera_t2
date_t1
date_t2
date_t3
```

During training only, the loss also uses:

```text
teacher_cached_t2_layers
```

where `teacher_cached_t2_layers` are extracted by running frozen VGGT on real `t2` images.

---

## 4. Tensor Shapes

Let:

```text
B       = batch size
S1      = number of t1 source views
S3      = number of t3 source views
S2      = number of target t2 views
T       = 5 + P
P       = number of patch tokens
D       = original VGGT cached feature dimension = 2048
d_model = bottleneck transformer dimension = 512
```

Each cached layer has shape:

```text
t1 cache layer:      [B, S1, T, 2048]
t3 cache layer:      [B, S3, T, 2048]
teacher t2 layer:   [B, S2, T, 2048]
```

The model predicts:

```text
predicted t2 layer: [B, S2, T, 2048]
```

The first five tokens are VGGT special tokens:

```text
tokens 0:5 = special tokens
tokens 5:  = patch tokens
```

The cache loss is applied only to patch tokens.

---

## 5. Main Modules

The model should contain the following modules.

### 5.1 Down Projection

Each source cached layer is projected from VGGT dimension `2048` to bottleneck dimension `512`.

For each cached layer:

```python
f1_low = down_proj(layer_norm(f1_cache))
f3_low = down_proj(layer_norm(f3_cache))
```

Shapes:

```text
f1_cache: [B, S1, T, 2048]
f3_cache: [B, S3, T, 2048]

f1_low:   [B, S1, T, 512]
f3_low:   [B, S3, T, 512]
```

There should be one down-projection per cached layer.

---

### 5.2 Learned Target-View Query

For each cached layer, create a learned `t2` query template.

Parameter shape:

```python
learned_t2_query[layer]: [1, 1, T, 512]
```

At runtime, expand it to:

```python
t2_query = learned_t2_query[layer].expand(B, S2, T, 512)
```

Runtime shape:

```text
t2_query: [B, S2, T, 512]
```

This query represents an empty target-view feature grid for the `t2` camera views. It is not copied from `t1`.

Each cached layer should have its own learned query parameter because different VGGT layers have different feature semantics.

---

### 5.3 Ray MLP

The ray MLP converts per-patch camera ray geometry into token embeddings.

Ray feature shape:

```text
ray_feat: [B, S, P, 8]
```

The eight ray features are:

```text
world ray direction:          3 values
normalized camera center:     3 values
normalized patch coordinates: 2 values
```

So:

```text
ray_dim = 8
```

The ray MLP maps:

```text
[B, S, P, 8] → [B, S, P, 512]
```

Implementation:

```python
class RayMLP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, ray_dim=8, d_model=512):
        super().__init__()
        self.net = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(ray_dim, d_model),
            nn.GELU(),
            nn.Linear(d_model, d_model),
        )

    def forward(self, ray_feat):
        return self.net(ray_feat)
```

Ray embeddings are added only to patch tokens:

```python
special = tokens[:, :, :5, :]
patches = tokens[:, :, 5:, :]

patches = patches + ray_mlp(ray_feat)

tokens = torch.cat([special, patches], dim=2)
```

This applies to:

```text
t1 source tokens
t3 source tokens
t2 target query tokens
```

---

### 5.4 Time Conditioning

Time conditioning is added to source and target tokens before the decoder.

The time features should encode:

```text
date_t1
date_t2
date_t3
tau = (t2 - t1) / (t3 - t1)
left gap = t2 - t1
right gap = t3 - t2
total gap = t3 - t1
```

The time-conditioning module maps the time feature vector to `512` dimensions.

For each temporal role:

```text
t1 source role
t3 source role
t2 target role
```

create a time embedding with shape:

```text
[B, 1, 1, 512]
```

Then add it to tokens:

```python
f1_low = f1_low + time_emb_t1
f3_low = f3_low + time_emb_t3
t2_query = t2_query + time_emb_t2
```

Time conditioning happens before the transformer decoder.

---

### 5.5 Source Memory Construction

For each cached layer, after down-projection, time conditioning, and ray conditioning:

```python
f1_low: [B, S1, T, 512]
f3_low: [B, S3, T, 512]
```

Flatten views and tokens:

```python
f1_mem = f1_low.reshape(B, S1 * T, 512)
f3_mem = f3_low.reshape(B, S3 * T, 512)
```

Concatenate them:

```python
memory = torch.cat([f1_mem, f3_mem], dim=1)
```

Final memory shape:

```text
memory: [B, (S1 + S3) * T, 512]
```

---

### 5.6 Target Query Construction

For each cached layer:

```python
t2_query = learned_t2_query[layer].expand(B, S2, T, 512)
```

Add time conditioning:

```python
t2_query = t2_query + time_emb_t2
```

Add ray conditioning to patch tokens:

```python
special = t2_query[:, :, :5, :]
patches = t2_query[:, :, 5:, :]

patches = patches + ray_mlp(ray_feat_t2)

t2_query = torch.cat([special, patches], dim=2)
```

Flatten for decoder input:

```python
query = t2_query.reshape(B, S2 * T, 512)
```

Shape:

```text
query: [B, S2 * T, 512]
```

---

## 6. Temporal Decoder

Each cached layer uses a one-block transformer decoder.

The decoder receives:

```text
query  = target t2 query tokens
memory = t1/t3 source tokens
```

The decoder block contains:

```text
self-attention on t2 query tokens
cross-attention from t2 query tokens to t1/t3 memory
MLP
LayerNorm
residual connections
```

The decoder uses:

```text
d_model = 512
num_heads = 8
mlp_ratio = 2.0
dropout = 0.1
num_decoder_blocks = 1
```

The decoder output shape is:

```text
h: [B, S2 * T, 512]
```

Reshape back to:

```python
h = h.reshape(B, S2, T, 512)
```

---

## 7. Up Projection

After the temporal decoder, project the target-view hidden tokens back to the VGGT cached feature dimension:

```python
pred_t2_cache = up_proj(h)
```

Shape:

```text
h:             [B, S2, T, 512]
pred_t2_cache: [B, S2, T, 2048]
```

There is one up-projection per cached layer.

The final model output is a list of four predicted cached layers:

```python
pred_cached_layers = [
    pred_layer_4,
    pred_layer_11,
    pred_layer_17,
    pred_layer_23,
]
```

Each predicted layer has shape:

```text
[B, S2, T, 2048]
```

---

## 8. Frozen VGGT Point Head

The VGGT point-map head is copied from the pretrained VGGT model and frozen.

```python
for p in self.point_head.parameters():
    p.requires_grad_(False)
```

The point head is not trained.

The predicted cached layers can be passed to the frozen point head to decode a predicted `t2` point map.

During the initial training stage, the point head is not part of the loss because the selected loss is cached-feature supervision only.

---

## 9. Training Target

During training, frozen VGGT is run on real `t2` images to extract teacher cached layers:

```python
teacher_cached_t2 = frozen_vggt_extract_cached_layers(t2_images)
```

The teacher cached layers must correspond to the same `t2` cameras used to build the target query.

For every cached layer:

```text
predicted t2 cache: [B, S2, T, 2048]
teacher t2 cache:   [B, S2, T, 2048]
```

These shapes must match exactly.

Add an assertion:

```python
assert pred.shape == teacher.shape
```

---

## 10. Loss Function

The training loss is:

```text
LayerNorm SmoothL1 cache loss + cosine cache loss
```

The loss is applied only to patch tokens.

For each cached layer:

```python
pred_patch = pred_cache[:, :, 5:, :]
teacher_patch = teacher_cache[:, :, 5:, :]
```

Normalize over the channel dimension:

```python
pred_norm = F.layer_norm(pred_patch, pred_patch.shape[-1:])
teacher_norm = F.layer_norm(teacher_patch, teacher_patch.shape[-1:])
```

Compute Smooth L1:

```python
loss_smooth = F.smooth_l1_loss(
    pred_norm,
    teacher_norm,
    beta=0.1,
)
```

Compute cosine loss:

```python
pred_flat = pred_norm.reshape(-1, pred_norm.shape[-1])
teacher_flat = teacher_norm.reshape(-1, teacher_norm.shape[-1])

loss_cos = 1.0 - F.cosine_similarity(
    pred_flat,
    teacher_flat,
    dim=-1,
    eps=1e-6,
).mean()
```

Layer loss:

```python
loss_layer = loss_smooth + 0.05 * loss_cos
```

Total cache loss across the four layers:

```python
loss_cache = sum(loss_layer_i for i in layers) / 4
```

Final training loss:

```python
loss = loss_cache
```

There is no point-map loss and no Chamfer loss in this implementation.

---

## 11. Loss Configuration

Use the following loss configuration:

```yaml
loss:
  cache_weight: 1.0
  cache_loss_type: smooth_l1
  cache_normalize: true
  cache_patch_only: true
  cache_smooth_l1_beta: 0.1
  cache_cos_weight: 0.05

  special_token_weight: 0.0
  pointmap_weight: 0.0
  chamfer_weight: 0.0
```

Only patch tokens are supervised.

Special tokens are not included in the first implementation.

